WEBVTT

00:26.026 --> 00:27.061
Mom?

00:27.861 --> 00:29.029
Right.

00:38.272 --> 00:39.407
(SIGHS)

01:30.324 --> 01:31.459
Jeez.

01:59.520 --> 02:00.754
DONNY: Hey, Chief.

02:00.788 --> 02:02.490
-Thought we said 9:00.
-(CLEARS THROAT)

02:04.158 --> 02:05.826
DONNY: Yeah.

02:05.859 --> 02:07.761
But new chief showed up early.

02:07.795 --> 02:10.531
Wants to gather the department
together first thing.

02:10.564 --> 02:12.200
So, since the department
is you and me,

02:12.233 --> 02:13.867
I figured
I'd come and get you.

02:13.901 --> 02:15.303
-Ooh, is that coffee?
-Mmm.

02:21.342 --> 02:22.543
(SNIFFS)

02:22.576 --> 02:24.345
Is that the box
you took from Ennis'?

02:24.378 --> 02:25.379
GLORIA: Uh-huh.

02:27.248 --> 02:28.449
Nathan at his dad's?

02:28.482 --> 02:29.517
Hopefully.

02:32.586 --> 02:33.721
Oh.

02:35.423 --> 02:37.525
Do you think
this Thaddeus Mobley fella

02:37.558 --> 02:38.992
had something to
do with the murder?

02:40.027 --> 02:41.562
GLORIA: I should say so,

02:43.197 --> 02:45.032
seeing as how Ennis Stussy

02:45.065 --> 02:47.067
and this Thaddeus Mobley
are one and the same.

02:47.868 --> 02:49.069
Come again?

02:51.772 --> 02:53.541
How's it you're in
my kitchen again?

02:54.542 --> 02:56.577
Oh, the chief...
Well, the new chief.

02:57.211 --> 02:59.547
Oh, right. The department.

03:02.783 --> 03:04.084
Well... (EXHALES)

03:04.752 --> 03:06.720
Let's go see
if I still have a job.

03:08.356 --> 03:10.358
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

03:31.211 --> 03:33.281
You going by
the autopsy later?

03:33.814 --> 03:35.215
They glued
his nose and mouth shut.

03:35.249 --> 03:38.185
Are we thinking cause of death
is somehow a cliffhanger?

03:38.218 --> 03:39.587
Guess not.

03:40.454 --> 03:41.755
Did you canvass the local?

03:41.789 --> 03:44.091
Any reports of
strange customers?

03:44.124 --> 03:45.593
Well, Earl at the Gas N Go

03:45.626 --> 03:47.395
intimated he might
have had a weird one.

03:47.428 --> 03:48.462
Weird how?

03:48.496 --> 03:50.731
Uh, Ron? It's... Hello?

03:50.964 --> 03:52.966
-RON: Hello.
-It's me.

03:53.000 --> 03:54.101
RON: Hello?

03:54.134 --> 03:57.237
-Ron? Can you hear me?
-Is this you, Gloria?

03:57.271 --> 03:59.740
I wanted to check on Nathan,
make sure he was getting...

03:59.773 --> 04:01.108
Ah, I can't quite hear you.

04:01.141 --> 04:02.810
-Ron, it's Gloria.
-Hello?

04:02.843 --> 04:04.578
-Hold on, I'll call you...
-What's that?

04:04.812 --> 04:06.280
(SIGHS) Gosh.

04:06.314 --> 04:07.715
Does yours do that?

04:07.748 --> 04:08.782
Who?

04:08.816 --> 04:09.950
Every time I make a call,

04:09.983 --> 04:11.852
it's like
I'm in a silent movie.

04:12.586 --> 04:13.587
(SIGHS)

04:42.282 --> 04:44.485
Hold up, forgot my gun.

04:55.396 --> 04:57.365
I'm here, right? You see me.

04:57.398 --> 04:58.966
Is that a trick question?

05:10.143 --> 05:11.311
IRV: "Keep it."

05:11.579 --> 05:13.213
SY: That's what he said.

05:13.246 --> 05:16.384
This V.M. Vargas?

05:16.417 --> 05:19.019
Yes. And we should have...

05:19.052 --> 05:20.688
At the time when
we needed the loan,

05:20.721 --> 05:22.490
we should have come to you.

05:23.424 --> 05:26.093
Any idea what the V.M.
stands for?

05:31.198 --> 05:33.701
You borrowed
$1,000,000 from a man

05:33.734 --> 05:34.968
without knowing
his first name.

05:35.002 --> 05:36.770
-I know how it...
-IRV: It's not a question.

05:37.170 --> 05:39.540
I'm just assessing
the level of stupidity.

05:39.573 --> 05:40.641
-Hey, hey.
-Irv, come on,

05:40.674 --> 05:41.975
we don't have to...

05:42.009 --> 05:43.677
You get a lot of
business from us.

05:43.711 --> 05:45.413
Which, boychik,
will stop the moment

05:45.446 --> 05:47.180
they arrest you
for money laundering.

05:47.214 --> 05:48.649
At which time,
all your business

05:48.682 --> 05:50.684
goes to a criminal attorney.

05:50.718 --> 05:52.586
And might I recommend
Bruce Lipshits

05:52.620 --> 05:53.887
in our Minneapolis office?

05:53.921 --> 05:56.790
-We're not asking for...
-Irv, stop screwing around.

05:57.858 --> 06:01.529
I need you to do some digging
on this guy, his outfit.

06:01.562 --> 06:03.096
Now, we gave you his card

06:03.130 --> 06:05.365
and the card
his reps gave to us last year.

06:05.399 --> 06:07.067
You have the loan document,

06:07.100 --> 06:09.102
on which is a phone number
and a mailing address.

06:09.136 --> 06:11.505
There's also
a corporate ID number!

06:11.539 --> 06:13.273
So unless you got
the brains of a monkey,

06:13.306 --> 06:14.608
you should be able to friend

06:14.642 --> 06:16.944
this cocksucker on Facebook,
and reel him in.

06:19.212 --> 06:20.280
And then?

06:21.882 --> 06:25.218
Then we get him to
take his money back

06:25.252 --> 06:26.820
and forget he ever met us.

06:38.165 --> 06:39.166
(SNIFFS)

06:41.635 --> 06:42.770
How's Stella?

06:43.003 --> 06:44.572
Yeah, she's good.

06:46.940 --> 06:48.909
You think I was
too hard on him?

06:50.444 --> 06:51.579
Irv?

06:51.612 --> 06:52.713
Ray.

06:52.746 --> 06:54.448
At the anniversary party.

06:55.483 --> 06:59.553
Look, he...
It's been a long time coming,

06:59.587 --> 07:01.121
you saying no to him.

07:01.154 --> 07:03.757
-Haven't I always...
-Nuh-nuh-nuh. (LAUGHS)

07:03.991 --> 07:07.461
Like a Swiss watch.
Reliable. That's you.

07:07.495 --> 07:09.797
-So he should have no...
-Yeah, but...

07:09.830 --> 07:11.298
-Lookit, don't go...
-(SIGHS)

07:12.933 --> 07:14.768
We've been
friends a long time.

07:14.802 --> 07:16.470
Don't go getting soft here.

07:16.504 --> 07:20.007
We talked about this.
It's for his own good.

07:20.508 --> 07:21.675
A man like that,

07:21.709 --> 07:23.310
used to blaming
others for his...

07:23.343 --> 07:25.145
Maybe I should just
give him the stamp.

07:25.178 --> 07:26.947
To what end?

07:28.649 --> 07:30.283
You think that'll fix it?

07:30.317 --> 07:33.120
Next thing he's going
to want is interest.

07:33.654 --> 07:35.856
It's envy, the green monster.

07:36.624 --> 07:38.626
-Your brother's a loser.
-He's not a loser.

07:38.659 --> 07:41.795
Well, he's doing
a pretty good imitation.

07:43.296 --> 07:46.667
And you're the goddamn
Parking Lot King of Minnesota.

07:47.735 --> 07:49.202
He doesn't want
the stamp, pal.

07:49.236 --> 07:50.738
He wants your life.

07:54.875 --> 07:56.877
(TYPING SLOWLY)

08:06.987 --> 08:08.055
IRV: Deb?

08:12.325 --> 08:13.961
What's it doing?

08:13.994 --> 08:15.796
You hit "Enter"?

08:15.829 --> 08:16.997
What's "Enter"?

08:17.030 --> 08:18.331
It's a... (SIGHS)

08:33.013 --> 08:34.582
Now what do I...

08:42.590 --> 08:43.724
Wait!

08:52.032 --> 08:53.300
What happened?

08:53.567 --> 08:55.202
Did I...

08:55.235 --> 08:56.369
What did I...

08:56.403 --> 08:57.437
I don't know.

08:57.470 --> 08:59.406
-It just went.
-Uh-huh.

08:59.439 --> 09:01.141
I'll check mine.

09:08.248 --> 09:10.017
Mine's out, too.

09:10.050 --> 09:11.418
Is it the power?

09:14.221 --> 09:15.989
I mean, the lights are on.

09:17.658 --> 09:20.594
I'll call the IT kid
that Shirley knows.

09:29.803 --> 09:31.639
(MUSIC PLAYING)

09:58.531 --> 10:01.802
VARGAS: Zdraveyte,
as the Bulgarians say.

10:01.835 --> 10:02.903
Pardon?

10:02.936 --> 10:05.105
Ni hao  is the Chinese.

10:05.138 --> 10:08.676
The Corsicans use
the simple salut.

10:08.709 --> 10:11.378
And guten Tag,
if German's your thing.

10:14.347 --> 10:16.183
Is that... Are they with you?

10:17.350 --> 10:18.719
Surmise.

10:19.119 --> 10:20.187
ATTENDANT: What?

10:20.220 --> 10:23.724
Because we arrived together,
we are together. Surmise.

10:24.491 --> 10:26.359
-Well, are ya?
-Yes.

10:28.495 --> 10:29.930
Can't park that here.

10:29.963 --> 10:32.299
We got...
City's got an ordinance.

10:32.666 --> 10:34.467
No, it's perfectly fine.

10:34.501 --> 10:37.570
Mr. Stussy himself
gave me permission.

10:37.905 --> 10:39.006
Who?

10:39.406 --> 10:40.908
Your employer.

10:42.876 --> 10:46.313
You do see the sign
above which you stand,

10:46.346 --> 10:48.682
and how a man
with a keener sense of reason

10:48.716 --> 10:50.851
might extrapolate a connection

10:50.884 --> 10:52.720
with the name
I just mentioned.

10:53.186 --> 10:54.321
Your boss.

10:55.555 --> 10:57.424
-Look, mister...
-We're done here.

10:59.526 --> 11:01.428
(MUSIC CONTINUES PLAYING)

11:28.621 --> 11:29.857
(TRUCK DOOR CLOSES)

11:32.625 --> 11:33.894
(BANGS ON TRUCK)

11:39.399 --> 11:41.902
Okay then. Just... It's fine.

11:41.935 --> 11:44.872
Like he said,
he's got permission.

11:47.875 --> 11:50.243
No, I won't say
"from Mr. Stussy."

11:50.277 --> 11:51.578
I'm not gonna create

11:51.611 --> 11:53.713
the implication
of foreknowledge.

11:55.282 --> 11:58.551
Of... Knowing before the fact.

11:59.820 --> 12:02.389
They have permission.
They can park there.

12:02.422 --> 12:03.623
Thanks.

12:17.237 --> 12:19.472
Did you see this
bullshit in the paper?

12:20.107 --> 12:22.109
Some old-timer
out in the country,

12:22.142 --> 12:24.144
they push in his
front door, tie him up.

12:24.177 --> 12:27.480
He runs a general store,
and some hopped-up junkie

12:27.514 --> 12:29.449
thinks he takes
the register money home.

12:31.985 --> 12:33.921
(SIGHS) Ennis Stussy.

12:34.955 --> 12:36.756
Eighty-two years old.

12:39.793 --> 12:41.128
Not the Minnesota
I grew up in,

12:41.161 --> 12:42.195
I'll tell you that.

12:42.963 --> 12:44.497
It's a tragedy.

12:45.465 --> 12:48.601
Do you need something?

12:50.270 --> 12:52.505
Oh, uh... There's...

12:56.776 --> 12:59.980
Maybe a problem, not sure yet.

13:00.547 --> 13:02.315
Just, this Vargas fella...

13:02.349 --> 13:04.151
I got a call
from the Oakbridge lot.

13:04.484 --> 13:05.618
The raised one?

13:05.652 --> 13:07.454
No. Ground lot,
under the highway.

13:07.487 --> 13:09.556
-Doesn't get a lot of traffic.
-Right.

13:11.058 --> 13:13.126
Why'd we buy that one again?

13:13.160 --> 13:14.494
Sprawl-wise,
you thought it'd be

13:14.527 --> 13:16.029
a good investment long-term.

13:16.063 --> 13:17.764
Maybe turn it
into condos one day.

13:17.797 --> 13:19.032
Right.

13:19.066 --> 13:20.834
We should talk
to Stan Grossman about that.

13:20.868 --> 13:22.035
Test the waters.

13:22.069 --> 13:24.637
Yeah. I'll make a note.

13:25.705 --> 13:29.176
Anyway, it seems there's
a big rig parked there now.

13:29.642 --> 13:31.011
-In the lot?
-SY: Mmm-hmm.

13:31.044 --> 13:32.312
Well, that's against code.

13:32.345 --> 13:34.147
Well, okay. There's that, too.

13:34.181 --> 13:37.584
But more to the point,
what's in it?

13:38.685 --> 13:41.454
And I'm a little troubled
by the escalation.

13:41.488 --> 13:43.891
Money loaned is
one thing, but this?

13:43.924 --> 13:45.592
A truck full of...

13:46.059 --> 13:47.360
Well...

13:48.428 --> 13:51.531
It could be anything.
Booze, guns...

13:51.564 --> 13:53.700
The kind of demeanor
this fella has...

13:54.567 --> 13:56.536
You think maybe it's...

13:56.569 --> 13:58.071
I don't even
wanna say it out loud.

13:58.538 --> 13:59.873
Slave girls?

14:00.573 --> 14:02.109
What? No.

14:02.876 --> 14:05.545
I was gonna say drugs.
You think it's slave girls?

14:08.281 --> 14:09.349
No.

14:10.683 --> 14:12.052
I mean, he's capable,

14:12.085 --> 14:13.520
this Vargas fella,
don't you think?

14:13.553 --> 14:14.721
Just from the one meeting.

14:17.724 --> 14:20.527
We should probably
drive over there, take a look.

14:22.429 --> 14:26.900
Or, and this is
the other way to go, not.

14:27.800 --> 14:31.271
See, I'm thinking
about deniability.

14:31.304 --> 14:33.240
What they call "plausible."

14:33.273 --> 14:34.874
-'Cause if we...
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

14:35.775 --> 14:39.079
Look,
if Irv's right, and we...
(MOUTHING)

14:39.779 --> 14:41.081
Then we know.

14:41.714 --> 14:43.116
Which, in a court of law...

14:43.150 --> 14:44.551
Got it.

14:44.584 --> 14:48.155
That's... You're...
Good thinking.

14:52.559 --> 14:53.860
So, what do we...

14:53.893 --> 14:57.064
I think we gotta wait
and see what Irv turns up.

14:57.097 --> 14:58.932
Then, whatever dirt, we use

14:58.966 --> 15:01.268
to extricate
ourselves overall.

15:05.838 --> 15:07.474
(SIGHS DEEPLY)

15:07.507 --> 15:09.776
MOE: This is
the problem right here.

15:11.578 --> 15:13.446
It's not even
a proper police station.

15:14.914 --> 15:16.783
Where do you keep prisoners?

15:16.816 --> 15:19.652
There's a store room,
computer boxes, paper towels,

15:19.686 --> 15:22.089
or we drive 'em
10 miles to Paynesville.

15:23.856 --> 15:27.127
Wait, you said computer boxes.
Where are the computers?

15:27.160 --> 15:29.796
They're in the boxes.
Chief doesn't like computers.

15:29.829 --> 15:31.864
Well, old chief. Sorry, Chief.

15:33.666 --> 15:34.834
Oh, you don't like them?

15:34.867 --> 15:36.303
It's not that
I don't like them.

15:36.336 --> 15:38.105
I don't like them,
but that's not...

15:38.438 --> 15:39.806
The old way works just fine.

15:39.839 --> 15:42.009
Type out a report,
send it via telex.

15:42.342 --> 15:44.177
You do know
what year it is, right?

15:44.611 --> 15:45.812
The future.

15:45.845 --> 15:47.714
We don't use...
Who uses telexes anymore?

15:48.281 --> 15:50.850
So that's why no one
ever writes me back.

15:53.186 --> 15:55.488
The point is, if I need
a record search or priors run,

15:55.522 --> 15:56.756
I just call Jerry at County.

15:56.789 --> 15:57.824
Yeah, or Lou-Ann,

15:57.857 --> 16:00.527
if Jerry's sick
or out or something.

16:02.695 --> 16:04.097
I'm sorry to be
doing this today,

16:04.131 --> 16:05.465
with the loss of
your father and all...

16:05.965 --> 16:07.234
Stepfather.

16:08.301 --> 16:09.369
But you need to
get with the program.

16:09.402 --> 16:10.503
It's not the '50s anymore

16:10.537 --> 16:11.938
where people
don't lock their front doors.

16:11.971 --> 16:13.973
People don't lock
their front doors. Not here.

16:14.407 --> 16:16.843
Although they might now,
after what happened to Ennis.

16:16.876 --> 16:18.145
I'm just saying.

16:24.317 --> 16:25.318
Chief...

16:25.985 --> 16:27.154
As much as I want to hear

16:27.187 --> 16:28.355
about this future
you've come from,

16:28.388 --> 16:30.023
I got a potential
witness to interview

16:30.057 --> 16:32.692
who may have seen our perp
gas up on his way out of town.

16:32.725 --> 16:34.394
-So I'm gonna...
-MOE: You know what?

16:36.063 --> 16:37.364
I'm gonna go ahead and pretend

16:37.397 --> 16:38.698
you didn't just
mouth off to me

16:38.731 --> 16:40.100
like my teenage daughter.

16:41.901 --> 16:43.036
And I'm gonna go ahead

16:43.070 --> 16:44.304
and let you
brace your witness.

16:44.337 --> 16:46.673
And then I'm gonna let you
take a few days off to grieve.

16:47.574 --> 16:49.542
But this is a done deal.

16:49.576 --> 16:50.743
You're being
absorbed by the county.

16:50.777 --> 16:52.245
You work for me now.

16:52.279 --> 16:54.047
So, when you get back,

16:54.081 --> 16:57.250
you and the Chief, me,

16:58.251 --> 16:59.352
are gonna have a long talk

16:59.386 --> 17:01.088
about the way
things work around here.

17:07.260 --> 17:09.762
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

17:27.114 --> 17:29.949
EARL: I told Donny.
It was the Russians.

17:31.151 --> 17:33.453
No. I think
he would've mentioned that.

17:33.486 --> 17:36.823
This is Thursday night, yeah?
'Round 10:00 p.m.?

17:37.624 --> 17:38.791
Why don't you start
from the beginning?

17:39.959 --> 17:42.595
You know, it's whaddaya,
Thursday. I got the game on.

17:42.629 --> 17:44.097
-Vikings?
-Gophers.

17:44.131 --> 17:46.099
And it's one of those nights.

17:46.133 --> 17:47.267
Miller, Miller Lite,

17:47.300 --> 17:49.469
cigarettes, cigarettes,
motor oil.

17:49.502 --> 17:51.604
And then some
twitchy kid comes in,

17:51.638 --> 17:53.440
wants a case of
frozen orange juice

17:53.473 --> 17:55.208
concentrate, which...

17:55.242 --> 17:57.144
Is that...
Can you make meth from that?

17:57.177 --> 17:58.911
Not last I heard.

17:58.945 --> 18:01.448
Maybe just
a vitamin deficiency.

18:01.481 --> 18:03.283
My point is,

18:03.316 --> 18:05.452
I'm already primed for...

18:05.485 --> 18:07.120
And then
this fella comes in...

18:07.154 --> 18:09.989
-"Fella" singular?
-If singular means just one.

18:10.022 --> 18:11.958
And he's looking for,
wants to know,

18:11.991 --> 18:13.626
do I have a phone book?

18:13.660 --> 18:15.395
And you're saying
this fella was Russian?

18:15.428 --> 18:17.063
Yes, ma'am.

18:17.096 --> 18:18.665
From, like, an accent, or...

18:20.267 --> 18:22.135
Well, now,
I can't rightly say.

18:22.169 --> 18:23.570
Maybe he told me.

18:23.603 --> 18:26.573
Well, like I said,
I got the Gophers on.

18:26.606 --> 18:28.975
But it's strong,
how I remember him.

18:29.008 --> 18:30.610
So, I showed him
where the book was,

18:30.643 --> 18:31.811
keep it on a chain.

18:31.844 --> 18:33.746
Why do you keep
your phone book on a chain?

18:33.780 --> 18:35.148
Well, remember in the '70s?

18:35.182 --> 18:36.949
People used to steal 'em.

18:37.850 --> 18:41.354
Anyhoo,
he looks through it, and then

18:43.456 --> 18:45.158
just tears a page out.

18:45.192 --> 18:48.161
Which, it's a public book,
which... Meant for everyone.

18:48.195 --> 18:49.862
So, I raise a ruckus.

18:49.896 --> 18:51.264
Can I see it?

18:51.298 --> 18:53.500
(INDISTINCT SPORTS COMMENTARY
ON RADIO)

19:14.221 --> 19:16.088
-Hey!
-Gotta take this as evidence.

19:16.889 --> 19:18.057
Evidence of what?

19:18.891 --> 19:22.028
Well, fella stopped in here,

19:22.061 --> 19:23.230
used your phone book,
tore out the page

19:23.263 --> 19:25.031
with Ennis' information on it.

19:25.064 --> 19:27.033
Shortly thereafter,
Ennis is asphyxiated.

19:27.066 --> 19:29.336
So, I'd say,
evidence he was looking for

19:29.369 --> 19:31.504
Ennis' house but
didn't know the address.

19:43.115 --> 19:45.218
"And in time of great joy,

19:45.252 --> 19:48.087
"they had meat
and fowl and grain.

19:48.621 --> 19:51.258
"And in time of sorrow,
they ate tears."

19:52.959 --> 19:55.127
(PAROLEE HUMMING)

